<definition>
    <statement>
        <p>
           Given and angle <m>\theta</m> in the unit circle, where the corresponding point on the unit circle is <m>(x,y)</m>,
           we define the <term>cosine</term> and <term>sine</term> of <m>\theta</m> as
           <md>
            <mrow>\cos(\theta)= \amp </mrow>
            <mrow>\sin(\theta)= \amp </mrow>
           </md>
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>
<p>
    Below we have the illustration of <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta)</m>, with a right triangle embedded in the unit circle. This allows us to use the Pythagorean Theorem to find exact values of these functions when <m>\theta</m> is one of a few special angles.
</p>
        <image>
<prefigure label = "unit_circ2" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(500,500)" margins="(200,5,200,5)">
